A Neue Wissenschaft
In this summer, a unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers met to ponder the necessity of a new science that could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In light of the great challenges, it is believed that there is only little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory) which require enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World to be explored. Secondly, data collection, which means work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution must be based on scientific principles, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, many believe that the only difficult part of the work would lie in using already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
The models of today do work.
However, an increasing group of scientists points out phenomena that cannot be explained very well with today's theories.
Although these problems are increasingly appearing, they are also skillfully circumvented because the science with which these problems could be explained simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is quite securely established.
Physics, at least the part we encounter as ordinary people, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – while there are still a few things in our bodies we don't understand, it is assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Moreover, there are still the new social sciences that deal with people and societies.
In each of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and mostly also free from dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In very rare cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field because these worlds and languages are so different.
This means that we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the inclusion of several disciplines.
Think, for example, of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interactions occur on the basis of physics. The information transmitted during these interactions is conveyed due to the laws of electricity.
Additionally, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and transmit information in this process.
When interacting between two brains, a new level is added: Here, information exchange occurs through language, symbols, and ideas.
On each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes on these levels.
Information is exchanged between these levels as well, but there is no science that even begins to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this gap, some scientists have tried to redefine the tools for explaining processes within one level and then apply them to another level.
These attempts then lead to something like "language" on the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem is not solved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the different levels and how is it transmitted?
Now almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from various countries and fields and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
Besides scientists from the relevant disciplines, artists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," where scientific foundations from one level are adapted and extended to another.
Others, however, believe that a completely new approach is necessary.
From their perspective, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents, and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge through scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Fully free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that bear the sign of "science" have, similar to their counterparts in the world of business, developed an institutional character.
One believes that developing countries should build up similar resources as industrial countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Viele junge Wissenschaftler erleben derzeit eine Revolution und viele dieser – manchmal revolutionären – Ideen stammen aus Laboratorien und Forschungszentren, die nicht mit den großen Institutionen in Zusammenhang stehen.
Die durchdachtesten Ansätze im Bereich mathematischer Algorithmen kamen zwanzig Jahre lang aus der Sowjetunion, wo es an allen Ecken und Enden an Rechnerkapazitäten mangelte.
Die genialsten und im wahrsten Sinne des Wortes weltbewegenden Erkenntnisse im Bereich Physik der letzten Jahrzehnte kamen nicht wie erwartet aus den bekannten Innovationszentren, sondern aus Budapest.
Im Iran gibt es eine Tradition der Architektur, die Kognitionswissenschaftlern zu wichtigen Erkenntnissen verhalf.
Und die radikalsten neuen Ideen im Bereich der zweiten Generation künstlicher Intelligenz (die so genannten „autonomen Agenten“) stammen heute aus Prag.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, he changed the identity of space and time. The FIS Conference in July was the unannounced start of an attempt to redefine the universe in this manner.
These gaps were identified, for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be included in this group to identify those issues that could be resolved once this new science is developed, or discovered if one wants to put it that way.

